00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:29,400
Bubly: Toh basically, Python generators iterable objects ke liye iterable values ek hi samay mein utpann karte hain, jisse memory mein poori shreni ko sthan nahi dena padta

4
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,656
Bunty: Ek hi samay mein utpann karte hain, matlab samjho, ye yield keyword ka upyog karke kya karte hain?

5
00:00:38,256 --> 00:00:52,992
Bubly: Yield keyword ka upyog karke, ve ek value utpann karke baad mein usi avastha se chalne lagte hain, jaise ki ek pyaala mein paani bharte hain, har baar ek glass paani nikalte hain, na ki poora tank le aate hain

6
00:00:53,592 --> 00:01:06,768
Bunty: Wah, yeh toh bahut acha analogy hai, ab samajh aaya ki Python generators kyun memory-efficient hote hain, par bade datasets ya anant shreniyon ka prakriya karne ke liye inka kya fayda hai?

7
00:01:07,368 --> 00:01:23,856
Bubly: Bade datasets ya anant shreniyon ka prakriya karne ke liye, Python generators uttam banate hain, kyunki ve ek value utpann karte hain, uska upyog karte hain, phir agle value ko utpann karte hain, isse memory ka upyog bahut kam hota hai

8
00:01:24,456 --> 00:01:35,496
Bunty: Acha acha, toh basically, Python generators humein memory-efficient tareeke se bade datasets ko handle karne ka mauka dete hain, ye bahut faydemand hai

9
